And again, I'm just
taking volunteers today.

00:11:32.490 --> 00:11:35.720 align:middle line:84%
So again, lots of
information on those

00:11:35.720 --> 00:11:38.090 align:middle line:84%
slides just kind of
appeared on one slide

00:11:38.090 --> 00:11:40.100 align:middle line:90%
and I didn't belabor it.

00:11:40.100 --> 00:11:42.110 align:middle line:84%
The basic idea in
computer science

00:11:42.110 --> 00:11:45.230 align:middle line:84%
is that most nodes
are trustworthy.

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:47.510 align:middle line:84%
They're going to
follow the protocol.

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:53.180 align:middle line:84%
But a handful of nodes or
actors are either faulty,

00:11:53.180 --> 00:11:55.430 align:middle line:84%
in the sense of the
computer doesn't work well,

00:11:55.430 --> 00:11:58.520 align:middle line:84%
or nefarious in the sense
that they're determined

00:11:58.520 --> 00:12:00.450 align:middle line:90%
to undercut the system.

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:04.670 align:middle line:84%
So the basic premise is, most
nodes are honest in the sense

00:12:04.670 --> 00:12:08.690 align:middle line:84%
that they're going to
follow the algorithm.

00:12:08.690 --> 00:12:10.910 align:middle line:84%
In economics, it's
a dismal science.

00:12:10.910 --> 00:12:12.800 align:middle line:90%
We don't trust anybody.

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:18.050 align:middle line:84%
So everyone, on the other
hand, can be given incentives.

00:12:18.050 --> 00:12:23.780 align:middle line:84%
So we assume maximizing utility
or profit-maximizing behavior.

00:12:23.780 --> 00:12:25.670 align:middle line:84%
And then we load
things up in a way

00:12:25.670 --> 00:12:30.140 align:middle line:84%
that even though there are
secrets, like preference shocks

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:33.530 align:middle line:84%
or unobserved states
and so on, the actors

00:12:33.530 --> 00:12:38.800 align:middle line:84%
have an incentive to reveal
what those states are.

00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:42.460 align:middle line:84%
So the message is, as
in mechanism design

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:45.520 align:middle line:84%
that we did earlier
in the lecture,

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:48.070 align:middle line:90%
are part of the contract.

00:12:48.070 --> 00:12:51.370 align:middle line:84%
And they're going
to be sent honestly.

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:54.790 align:middle line:84%
But it's due to the
incentive constraints.

00:12:54.790 --> 00:12:56.410 align:middle line:84%
And without the
incentive constraints,

00:12:56.410 --> 00:13:00.100 align:middle line:84%
we kind of assume
everyone's going to cheat.

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:05.060 align:middle line:84%
So it is kind of a
philosophical difference.

00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:06.890 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, that's
why, in the lecture

00:13:06.890 --> 00:13:13.300 align:middle line:84%
I put the discussion of
bitcoin and other algorithms

00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:19.890 align:middle line:84%
in the context of mechanism
design to draw this contrast.

00:13:19.890 --> 00:13:23.390 align:middle line:90%
OK, so that's the review sheet.

00:13:23.390 --> 00:13:29.090 align:middle line:84%
And let's get to
don't lecture here.

00:13:29.090 --> 00:13:31.600 align:middle line:90%


00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:37.940 align:middle line:84%
OK, so today part two,
more on contracts.

00:13:37.940 --> 00:13:42.010 align:middle line:84%
So the application is going
to be financial markets.

00:13:42.010 --> 00:13:45.820 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to try to figure
out what kind of contracts

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:48.850 align:middle line:84%
a small business would
write with a lender.

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:53.020 align:middle line:84%
In particular, what the
underlying obstacles to trade

00:13:53.020 --> 00:13:53.590 align:middle line:90%
are.

00:13:53.590 --> 00:13:57.820 align:middle line:84%
We're going to want to identify,
from data using the theory,

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:02.080 align:middle line:84%
what those obstacles are
that limit the ability to go

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:03.910 align:middle line:84%
into business or
limit the ability

00:14:03.910 --> 00:14:08.350 align:middle line:84%
to finance the business once
you're already in business.

00:14:08.350 --> 00:14:10.870 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
economics part of it.

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:13.360 align:middle line:84%
The technique part
of it is, we're

00:14:13.360 --> 00:14:17.200 align:middle line:84%
going to do a structural
estimation of the model.

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:22.210 align:middle line:84%
But we will also look at some
reduced form techniques that

00:14:22.210 --> 00:14:24.130 align:middle line:84%
are data summaries
that are consistent

00:14:24.130 --> 00:14:25.900 align:middle line:90%
with the structural model.

00:14:25.900 --> 00:14:28.090 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, we use
reduced-form techniques

00:14:28.090 --> 00:14:30.700 align:middle line:84%
to identify stylized
facts different

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:31.970 align:middle line:90%
across different regions.

00:14:31.970 --> 00:14:34.180 align:middle line:84%
And then we use
the theory to try

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:36.070 align:middle line:84%
to make sense of
what we're seeing.

00:14:36.070 --> 00:14:38.440 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of an
experimental laboratory.

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:41.240 align:middle line:84%
And there are going to be
two sources of constraints.

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:45.580 align:middle line:84%
So one is for short, a
collateral constraint.

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:49.330 align:middle line:84%
Agents can borrow, but
potentially not much.

00:14:49.330 --> 00:14:52.630 align:middle line:84%
In order to borrow, they
have to post collateral

00:14:52.630 --> 00:14:54.640 align:middle line:84%
so that the amount
they can borrow

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:58.120 align:middle line:90%
is limited by their wealth.

00:14:58.120 --> 00:15:02.800 align:middle line:84%
That means low-wealth households
may not borrow very much.

00:15:02.800 --> 00:15:06.790 align:middle line:84%
And it may not make sense
to go into a business at all

00:15:06.790 --> 00:15:10.180 align:middle line:84%
because they can only operate
at a very small scale.

00:15:10.180 --> 00:15:13.060 align:middle line:84%
Or if they do go into
business, because it's the best

00:15:13.060 --> 00:15:15.610 align:middle line:84%
alternative
notwithstanding, they

00:15:15.610 --> 00:15:18.820 align:middle line:84%
are not investing very much
because of that collateral

00:15:18.820 --> 00:15:19.930 align:middle line:90%
constraint.

00:15:19.930 --> 00:15:23.260 align:middle line:84%
Now when there's a collateral
constraint that's binding,

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:27.320 align:middle line:84%
the borrowing is a
proportion of wealth.

00:15:27.320 --> 00:15:30.380 align:middle line:84%
So if you're thinking about
going across different firms

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:35.120 align:middle line:84%
in the cross section,
as net worth increases,

00:15:35.120 --> 00:15:41.260 align:middle line:84%
borrowing would increase, again,
for constrained entrepreneurs.

00:15:41.260 --> 00:15:43.030 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, it
doesn't necessarily

00:15:43.030 --> 00:15:45.550 align:middle line:84%
mean that with this collateral
constraint everyone's

00:15:45.550 --> 00:15:46.930 align:middle line:90%
going to be borrowing.

00:15:46.930 --> 00:15:51.370 align:middle line:84%
They may have enough wealth
to entirely self-finance.

00:15:51.370 --> 00:15:56.800 align:middle line:84%
Or the borrowing constraint
isn't binding in the sense

00:15:56.800 --> 00:15:58.690 align:middle line:84%
that they don't go
up to the limit.

00:15:58.690 --> 00:15:59.650 align:middle line:90%
They have some wealth.

00:15:59.650 --> 00:16:01.720 align:middle line:84%
They borrow
additional resources.

00:16:01.720 --> 00:16:05.000 align:middle line:84%
But they could have borrowed
more and they don't do it.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.320 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, a different
constraint is a moral hazard.

00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:12.970 align:middle line:84%
Now moral hazard means that,
it's a funny terminology.

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:16.870 align:middle line:84%
It's like you buy an
insurance policy that's

00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:20.410 align:middle line:84%
supposed to pay off if
your house burns down.

00:16:20.410 --> 00:16:22.750 align:middle line:84%
But because you're
insured, then you

00:16:22.750 --> 00:16:27.190 align:middle line:84%
don't pay attention and take
the appropriate precautionary

00:16:27.190 --> 00:16:28.300 align:middle line:90%
measures.

00:16:28.300 --> 00:16:31.510 align:middle line:84%
So the house is
likely to burn down.

00:16:31.510 --> 00:16:33.440 align:middle line:84%
For some reason, in
the insurance industry,

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:36.160 align:middle line:84%
this is referred
to as moral hazard

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:38.230 align:middle line:90%
as if it were, quote, "immoral."

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:41.300 align:middle line:84%
But again, from
our dismal science,

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:42.670 align:middle line:90%
economics point of view.

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:45.385 align:middle line:90%
It's not immoral, per se.

00:16:45.385 --> 00:16:48.550 align:middle line:84%
It's just that it didn't
have the right incentives.

00:16:48.550 --> 00:16:53.740 align:middle line:84%
And in this moral hazard world,
effort, diligence, taking care

00:16:53.740 --> 00:16:55.130 align:middle line:90%
is not observed.

00:16:55.130 --> 00:16:58.360 align:middle line:84%
So the only way the insurance
company or the lender

00:16:58.360 --> 00:17:03.100 align:middle line:84%
can get the money back is when
there's not an adverse event

00:17:03.100 --> 00:17:06.250 align:middle line:84%
or the firm is successful
in making profit.

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:08.680 align:middle line:84%
Now that means that
poor borrowers who

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:11.800 align:middle line:84%
owe a lot of money
don't have an incentive

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:14.500 align:middle line:84%
to work very hard at being
diligent because they're going

00:17:14.500 --> 00:17:16.359 align:middle line:84%
to pay the bulk of
their returns back

00:17:16.359 --> 00:17:18.670 align:middle line:84%
if they're successful
to the bank

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:21.140 align:middle line:90%
or to the insurance company.

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:22.930 align:middle line:90%
So they don't take care.

00:17:22.930 --> 00:17:25.660 align:middle line:84%
And the probability
of failure is high.

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:27.160 align:middle line:90%
It's a constraint.

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:28.960 align:middle line:84%
Because the
probability of failure

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:33.290 align:middle line:84%
could be high, especially
for low-wealth agents,

00:17:33.290 --> 00:17:35.780 align:middle line:84%
the banks, in order to
break even on those loans,

00:17:35.780 --> 00:17:37.970 align:middle line:84%
have to charge high
interest rates.

00:17:37.970 --> 00:17:40.415 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, the rate
could be so high,

00:17:40.415 --> 00:17:42.170 align:middle line:84%
it would be high
enough for the lender

00:17:42.170 --> 00:17:43.700 align:middle line:84%
to break even but
the borrower is

00:17:43.700 --> 00:17:49.730 align:middle line:84%
no longer interested because
it's just too high of a rate.

00:17:49.730 --> 00:17:52.700 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, high
rates, they may not

00:17:52.700 --> 00:17:56.280 align:middle line:84%
want to borrow very much, even
if they do go into business.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:17:58.820 align:middle line:84%
Another difference with
the collateral constraint

00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:02.840 align:middle line:84%
is in the moral hazard world,
the incentive constraint

00:18:02.840 --> 00:18:05.090 align:middle line:90%
is always binding.

00:18:05.090 --> 00:18:07.700 align:middle line:84%
That's a version of what
we were just discussing,

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:11.270 align:middle line:84%
full insurance is never optimal
because under full insurance,

00:18:11.270 --> 00:18:13.740 align:middle line:90%
you exert minimal effort.

00:18:13.740 --> 00:18:16.130 align:middle line:84%
So you don't offer
full insurance.

00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:18.890 align:middle line:84%
But likewise, then
effort it is lower

00:18:18.890 --> 00:18:21.300 align:middle line:84%
than it would have been in
a full information world.

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:25.970 align:middle line:84%
So the incentive constraint, to
be diligent, is always binding.

00:18:25.970 --> 00:18:30.230 align:middle line:84%
And the way out of that
problem, if in a cross section,

00:18:30.230 --> 00:18:33.110 align:middle line:84%
entrepreneurs have more and
more wealth comparing one

00:18:33.110 --> 00:18:36.080 align:middle line:84%
to the other, then they
can self-finance more.

00:18:36.080 --> 00:18:41.060 align:middle line:84%
And the more you self-finance,
the less you have to pay back.

00:18:41.060 --> 00:18:44.920 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, as wealth
goes up, borrowing goes down.

00:18:44.920 --> 00:18:46.930 align:middle line:84%
That's exactly the
opposite from what

00:18:46.930 --> 00:18:49.000 align:middle line:84%
we got in the limited
liability case

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.770 align:middle line:90%
for constrained entrepreneurs.

00:18:50.770 --> 00:18:52.790 align:middle line:84%
When wealth went up,
borrowing went up.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:56.260 align:middle line:84%
So I alluded to these
reduced-form statistics.

00:18:56.260 --> 00:19:00.040 align:middle line:84%
We will see again at some
point a summary of the data

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:03.730 align:middle line:84%
that, depending on the
region that they're in,

00:19:03.730 --> 00:19:07.390 align:middle line:84%
we will see either this one
result in the cross section

00:19:07.390 --> 00:19:09.230 align:middle line:90%
or the other one.

00:19:09.230 --> 00:19:14.080 align:middle line:84%
And the goal then is to
take the full-blown model

00:19:14.080 --> 00:19:16.270 align:middle line:84%
and do structural
estimates to determine

00:19:16.270 --> 00:19:17.920 align:middle line:90%
which constrain is binding.

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:18.850 align:middle line:90%
It could be one.

00:19:18.850 --> 00:19:19.780 align:middle line:90%
It could be the other.

00:19:19.780 --> 00:19:22.390 align:middle line:84%
Actually, technically,
it could be both.

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:26.500 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to show you that
once we review the tools we

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:29.740 align:middle line:84%
already have, pending on
the appropriate constraints,

00:19:29.740 --> 00:19:33.460 align:middle line:84%
it's actually easy to test
one versus the other versus

00:19:33.460 --> 00:19:34.600 align:middle line:90%
multiple.

00:19:34.600 --> 00:19:37.120 align:middle line:90%
It's relatively easy to do.

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:40.390 align:middle line:84%
But we are learning some
of those new tools today.

00:19:40.390 --> 00:19:43.340 align:middle line:84%
That's half of the
point of the lecture.

00:19:43.340 --> 00:19:48.100 align:middle line:84%
So I've made reference twice
to differences across regions.

00:19:48.100 --> 00:19:51.040 align:middle line:84%
I think I may have shown
